Over LF fence, over the crowd, and across the street

Doyle's ML debut Leonard was suffering from an injured finger
Into the crowd in front of RF bleachers
Moore's ML debut (and only career appearance)
With the count of 1-2, Mgr Cobb came out from the dugout and whispered something to catcher Woodall.  Harris then didn't get anything good to hit.
After going back and across at top speed, Wingo reached out with his gloved hand, juggled it a few times, and held on.
Hooper was summoned from the coaching lines at 3B
Hit in the back of the neck and was knocked down
Nice catch; reached over the grandstand railing
O'Rourke argued with Ump Geisel over safe call at 2B
SBH may've occurred during argument at 2B
Harrington's ML debut (and only career PA)
Wonderful 1-handed running catch at the scoreboard
Manush tried for 3B while O'Rourke was being run down
Bassler hit on finger by foul tip
After Danforth pitched one ball to Manush, Umpires Geisel and Moriarty took the ball away from him and a long argument ensued between Cobb, Sisler, and Severeid.
Robertson had Haney trapped between 2B & 3B but threw into LF; possible assists on the play.
Throw eluded Bassler but error charged to Manush

Combs was apparently run down 2X3(656) and called out.  When the Yanks protested, Ump Hildebrand said he hadn't seen the the play clearly and deferred to Ump Owens who called Combs safe.  Cobb ran in from CF to argue with all three umpires.
Ground rule triple to the circus seats
A glancing blow on the back of his head
Wells not credited with the win?  Cole entered the game with the lead and should've got the save.
Attempted double steal; no CS charged
Pipp attempted to force Tavener at 2B
Ground rule triple into the temporary circus seats
Combs ran in on it, missed, and it rolled towards the flagpole.
Threw past Pipp to the pavilion
Smith touched the ball as it went by and time was taken to examine his fingers.
Sensational catch against the bleacher wall
Smith turned his ankle and time was taken
Spurgeon slipped as he picked it up
Speaker took 3B when Tavener dropped O'Rourke's throw
Scored a hit though aided by Uhle's bad throw
Blue fumbled but recovered for an out while lying extended in the dirt.
McNulty stretched over the rope in RF to catch Cobb's drive
Over LF wall and struck a telephone pole across the street
The ball lodged behind some boards against the LF wall
The ball went among the temporary stands in RF
Haney fouled off a couple trying to bunt, then fanned
Hit top of concrete wall in LF and bounced into the street
A Sheely foul tip split one of Bassler's fingers
The Tigers did so much stalling (to give Wells more time to warm up) that Ump Owens called 'Ball 1' for Kamm before any pitch had been thrown to him.
Hit the top of the wall and bounded back.  Collins ran out to argue it was a home run but the umps disagreed.

Cleared the screen in LCF A lot of fans had gone home for supper thinking the Tigers were so far ahead they wouldn't be caught, but most of those who remained ran in from 3B to home plate with Cobb as he finished.  They screamed, threw new straw hats into the air, and pounded him on the back.
Into the circus stands in LCF
The Browns protested Ump Hildebrand's call at 2B when Sisler threw to LaMotte trying for the reverse DP.  Play halted for several minutes as the argument continued.
Ump Hildebrand called a strike on Cobb who broke his bat over the plate in protest.  Game halted for some time while he picked bat after bat before selecting a new one.
ej,willk101,P,hildg101,Obstruction non-call Williams protested that Bassler stepped on his foot when he started for 1B and was ejected by Ump Hildebrand.
Williams had gone to the bench but Ump Hildebrand halted the game until Kenny left the field.
Rigney drew a throw home; Galloway tried to intercept it but it bounced off his foot and into the Detroit dugout.
Cobb took a long lead and drew a throw to 2B from Perkins. As Cobb hurried back to 1B, O'Rourke scampered home, beating Dykes' throw by a narrow margin.
Over the high LCF scoreboard and out of the stadium, landing in the front yard of a residence.  One of the longest hits ever seen at Navin Field.
Ben Paschal was on leave of absence to S.Carolina where his wife was ill.
High over RF bleachers into Trumbull Avenue
Haney was injured sliding into 3B; time out taken
Over LF fence and into Cherry Street, a narrow avenue which parallels the LF wall.
Rolled to the flagpole in deepest CF; safe at home by inches
COURTESY RUNNER; Wingo was permitted to leave the field temporarily to put on new shoes.
Fans hooted Heilmann generously for snoozing
Schang nearly jumped out of his uniform when Ump Rowland called the bunt fair.
Rain delayed start of game by 49 minutes
Nice catch; wild throw trying to catch Wingo off 1B
